# Graphwise / PoolParty deployment stack — .gitignore
# Author: Kent Stroker

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Secrets and deployment-specific config
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# .env is the LIVE configuration for a particular deployment. It holds real
# passwords, client secrets, and encryption keys. Never commit it.
# Users clone this repo, run `cp env-config .env`, then edit .env with their
# own values.
.env

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Vendor license files
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Graphwise license files (PoolParty, GraphDB EE, UnifiedViews) are the
# vendor's property and are issued per-deployment. Each user obtains their
# own per files/licenses/README instructions. Never commit license blobs.
files/licenses/*.key
files/licenses/*.license

# scripts/cluster-bootstrap.sh writes files/dash.yaml -- a kubeconfig
# carrying a long-lived service-account bearer token for the dashboard.
# Generated per-deployment; never commit.
files/dash.yaml
files/.DS_Store

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Ontotext Refine vendor distribution
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# The platform-independent Refine zip (Java-based, no native binaries)
# is the workaround for ontotext/refine:1.2.x being amd64-only on
# Docker Hub. Operators drop the extracted dist into refine/ontorefine-*/
# locally; scripts/build-refine-image.sh wraps it in an arm64-compatible
# eclipse-temurin base + `kind load`s it. ~330MB; treat like a license
# file -- never commit.
refine/ontorefine-*/

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Extracted Keycloak realm exports
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# scripts/extract-poolparty-realm.sh writes a realm JSON containing client
# secrets and password hashes — vendor-distributed material that should not
# enter the public repo. Same treatment as license files.
charts/keycloak-realms/files/*.json

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Script / editor backups
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# setDomainName.sh and checkVersions.sh write <file>.bak alongside anything
# they modify. These are ephemeral review copies — the working file is the
# source of truth.
*.bak

# Editor swap files (vim, emacs, etc.)
*.swp
*.swo
*~

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# IDE and OS metadata
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# JetBrains (IntelliJ / PyCharm / WebStorm)
.idea/

# Visual Studio Code
.vscode/

# macOS Finder metadata
.DS_Store

# Linux / generic
.directory

# Claude Code local session state
.claude/

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Nested-subchart packaged tarballs
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Subcharts of subcharts (e.g. charts/addons/charts/unifiedviews-1.0.0.tgz)
# are PACKAGED snapshots that Helm prefers over the source directory at
# render time. Committing them creates a footgun: edits to the source
# subchart (e.g. charts/addons/charts/unifiedviews/) get masked by a
# stale tarball, the umbrella's own packaging includes BOTH copies, and
# operators end up debugging "why isn't my chart change taking effect".
# Always regenerate from source via `helm dependency update` on the
# umbrella; never commit the inner-subchart tarballs.
#
# The umbrella's own packaged tarballs (charts/graphwise-stack/charts/*.tgz)
# ARE committed -- they're the umbrella's vendored deps, deliberately
# pinned so deploys don't need network access.
charts/*/charts/*.tgz
charts/*/Chart.lock
# Re-include the umbrella's own bundled tarballs + lockfile -- those are
# intentional vendored deps, pinned so deploys don't need network. Only
# the nested-subchart-of-subchart tarballs (e.g. charts/addons/charts/*.tgz,
# charts/keycloak-realms/Chart.lock) are the footgun.
!charts/graphwise-stack/charts/*.tgz
!charts/graphwise-stack/Chart.lock

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Let's Encrypt state — deployment-specific, must never be committed
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# certbot writes cert + key material, account info, and logs under
# files/letsencrypt/. files/certbot/ holds the ACME challenge webroot
# (empty most of the time; populated briefly during issuance / renewal).
# Neither is meaningful outside a specific running deployment.
files/letsencrypt/
files/certbot/

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Terraform — local state + provider cache are per-deployment and can
# contain sensitive attributes (AWS resource IDs, EIPs, and in some
# provider versions, cleartext secrets). Never commit.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Provider plugin cache, regenerable with `terraform init`.
infra/terraform/.terraform/
# State files + sensitive plan dumps.
infra/terraform/terraform.tfstate
infra/terraform/terraform.tfstate.backup
infra/terraform/terraform.tfstate.*
infra/terraform/.terraform.tfstate.lock.info
infra/terraform/*.tfplan
# Per-deployment variable values. terraform.tfvars.example (the
# template) IS committed — the real terraform.tfvars with your AWS
# key pair name and admin CIDR is NOT.
infra/terraform/terraform.tfvars
infra/terraform/*.auto.tfvars
# NOTE: .terraform.lock.hcl is INTENTIONALLY NOT ignored. It pins the
# AWS provider version; committing it keeps teammates and CI in sync.

# Git credentials — NEVER commit. If `git config credential.helper store`
# is used, its output file goes here. The default location is
# ~/.git-credentials (outside any repo) — that's the safer place. These
# rules are the belt-and-suspenders guard in case the helper is
# misconfigured to land inside this directory.
.git-credentials
git.credentials
**/git.credentials
**/.git-credentials
*.credentials
